\begin_layout Subsubsection
Realibility assessment of the FFDI
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of this study is to explore long-term trends and variability in
 fire weather.
 First of all, the analysis examines the skill of the FFDI to represent
 fire weather in this region.
 This index was selected because its calibration used the Eucalyptus vegetation.
 These species dominate the landscape of bushfire-prone areas in Ecuador
 (see Chapter 2).
 In spirte of this, the index might still not accurately represent fire
 weatehr in the Ecuadorian Andes.
 The lack of fire activity records to directly valdiate the index demanded
 of the index's realiability assessment to use with alternative indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several analysis were conducted to test the realiability of the FFDI.
 First of all, linear correlations were computed between the FFDI and FFDI
 variables.
 The analysis used observations during the period 1997-2012.
 This analysis estableses if there is physical consistency among the relationshi
ps between fire weather variables and the index.
 Additionally, the investigation explored the monthly variability of the
 FFDI.
 The analysis used the cummulative FFDI metric—sum of daily FFDI values—.
 This analysis verifies if the index agrees with local bushfire reports.
 According to this information, fire activity intensifies during the season
 July-August-September (JAS) (see Chapter 2).
 Therefore it is expected that the FFDI represents this months with higer
 fire danger.
 Finally, the study computed seasonal FFDI time series.
 According to local report, the year 2012 was a particularly severe fire
 season (see Chapter 2).
 The time series should show 2012 with comparatively high fire danger if
 the if the FFDI is an accurate metric of the fire weather in this region.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even if the FFDI proves to be an accurate fire weather metric for this region,
 the length of the weather station records in Ecuador is short for the intended
 study.
 Therefore, this investigation applies methods described in previous chapters
 to extend the analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Computation of extended FFDI time series
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step to attemp extending the analysis was to compare the reanalysis
 data against observations.
 Plotting probability density functions (PDFs) and seasonal time series
 facilitated the analysis.
 The PDFs allowed the examination of the distribution of data and detect
 deviations from the mean.
 The time series allowed comparing trends, magnitudes and correlate data.
 The reanalysis variables that showed significant deviations from the observed
 climatology were bias-corrected.
 The bias-correction used linear scaling techniques.
 For relative humidity, the variables were bias-corrected for its recalculation
 (e.g.
 Specific humidity, see Appendix).
 Relative humidity was recalculated using the methods described in Chapter
 5.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI was computed with bias-corrected reanalysis data.
 These results were compared to FFDI data computed with observations.
 As in the previous step, plotting PDFs and time series allowed assessment
 of the FFDI results.
 The comparison of FFDI time series required defining a seasonal metric
 of the FFDI.
 Previous chapters used two metrics.
 The cumulative sum of daily values (FFDIcum) and the number of days with
 FFDI greater than 25 (FFDI>25).
 This analysis used only the FFDIcum metric because the danger classes in
 the FFDI scale are based on Australian fire cases (see Chapter 2).
\end_layout

