\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI is a useful metric of fire danger in the Ecuadorian Andes.
 First of all, it was calibrated with vegetation that also dominates fire-prone
 regions in Ecuador and Australia—Eucalyptus—.
 Additionally, the correlations with observed fire weather variables demonstrate
d a physically consistent behaviour.
 For example, temperature and relative humidity proved to be the most sensitive
 parameters of the index—as it is the case in Australia as well—.
 Most importantly, the FFDI represented as high fire danger months those
 considered to be of greater fire activity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The FFDI results showed that the Ecuadorian Andes experience higher fire
 danger from July to December.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Estacio2012"

\end_inset

 reports that JAS is the typical fire occurrence season in the city of Quito.
 This is the capital of the country and where more information about bushfires
 is available.
 Quito is located in the northern Ecuadorian Andes.
 Therefore, the fire reporting could be biased towards this region.
 There is scarce information about fire occurrences in other regions of
 the Ecuadorian Andes which might occur from November to December.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Pourrut1995"

\end_inset

 argue that the dry season for most of the Ecuadorian highlands is June-Septembe
r.
 Although, the authors also mention that a short dry period 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

veranillo
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occurs in December.
 Thefore, it is likely that fires can also occur in the months after JAS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results using the FFDI do not show that the year 2012 experienced high
 fire danger in comparison to other years.
 This constrast with the local reports which claim that 2012 was a severe
 fire activity year 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MinisteriodelAmbiente2013,SecretariadeAmbiente2013"

\end_inset

.
 The local appreciation for this year is not supported by long-term fire
 statistics and could be subjective.
 On the other hand, more robust tests of the realibility of the FFDI in
 this region also require fire activity information.
 Therefore, generating this informtion is of paramount importance to continue
 investigating this problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 20CR and ERA20C datasets are not suitable to investigate fire weather
 in the Ecuadorian Andes.
 These climate reconstructions showed weak—o even no correlation—with observatio
ns.
 The 20CR showed better results than the ERA-20C.
 However, the correlations with these data were not strong.
 Therefore, the analysis was not extended further back in time.
 Additionally, the bias-corrections did not improve the results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The discussion aims to further understand the limitations of 20CR and ERA-20C
 datasets in this region.
 The caveats of these datasets were acknowledged in previous chapters.
 However, the results showed biases that were unexpectedly large.
 Even more importantly, these datsets did not show to be capable of capturing
 climate variations in time.
 Therefore, the discussion will attempt to explain these discrepancies.
 Topography and the data assimilated in the reanalysis products are the
 main aspects examined.
 The discussion will also explore the feasibility of using alternative datasets
 and future work.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Topography is likely to cause major biases in the reanalysis data.
 Mountain ranges can block circulation and influence regional climate greatly
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Beniston2005"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, mountains can create a climate of their own 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ekhart1948"

\end_inset

.
 The Ecuadorian Andes comprise the Eastern and Western 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cordilleras
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (see Chapter 2).
 Meteorological stations in the Ecuadorian Andes are located in the inter-Andean
 valleys.
 The two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Cordilleras
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 surround these valleys.
 These plains experience a broad range of microclimates produced by the
 steep topography 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pourrut1995"

\end_inset

.
 The results show that 20CR and ERA-20C do not grasp the regional climate
 variability caused by this complex geographic region.
 In contrast, reanalysis performs well in Victoria, which is a region predominan
tly flat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nevertheless, reanalysis datasets have demonstrated better results in other
 mountain regions in the world.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Widmann1999"

\end_inset

 validated precipitation trends in the north-west United States from the
 National Centers for Environmental Prediction (NCEP) reanalysis.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
